user.biography: With #Artemis, @NASA will land the first woman and first person of color on the Moon. Take the next giant leap with us.

node.text: We've named the initial team of @NASAAstronauts to pave the way for human missions to the Moon under the #Artemis program. Now’s your chance to get to know them.

node.text: Join spacesuit engineer Lindsay Aitchison and singer Gregory Porter for a talk on next-generation spacesuits! Lindsay helped designed our new, Artemis generation spacesuits that will be worn on future missions to the Moon. The duo discuss the spacesuit worn in Gregory's latest music video, spacesuits for the Moon and our Perseverance rover's upcoming mission to Mars. 🚀

node.title: Next Generation Spacesuits for the Moon and Mars

node.text:
🎧 Our headquarters building in Washington, D.C., will soon be named after Mary W. Jackson, the first African-American female engineer at @NASA. Jackson started her NASA career in the West Area Computing Unit of the agency’s Langley Research Center in Hampton, Virginia. Jackson, a mathematician and aerospace engineer, went on to lead programs influencing the hiring and promotion of women in NASA's science, technology, engineering, and mathematics careers. In 2019, she was posthumously awarded the Congressional Gold Medal. 
Credit: NASA 
#HiddenFigures #NASA #NASAHQ #MaryJackson

node.title: NASA HQ has a new name

node.text: The next frontier isn’t just for the next generation – it’s for this generation. With our Artemis program, we will land the first woman and next man on the Moon by 2024. Then, we will use what we learn on and around the Moon to take the next giant leap – sending astronauts to Mars. We go, as Artemis.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by NASA Artemis on August 05, 2021 tagging @nasa, and @nasakennedy. May be an image of one or more people and people standing.

node.text:
Last week, NASA Administrator Bill Nelson visited the Space Launch System (SLS) in the Vehicle Assembly Building at @nasakennedy, as preparations for Artemis I launch continue.

The first in an increasingly complex set of missions, Artemis I will test SLS and Orion as an integrated system prior to crewed flights to the Moon. Through #Artemis, NASA will land the first woman and first person of color on the lunar surface, as well as establish a sustainable presence on and around the Moon.

Image credit: @NASA/Kim Shiflett

#nasa #exploration #Moon #rocket

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by NASA Artemis on July 31, 2021. May be an image of outdoors.

node.text:
They see me rollin’ 😎

#OTD 50 years ago Apollo 15 Commander David Scott became the first human to drive on another planetary body when he drove the lunar roving vehicle on the surface of the Moon.

Apollo 15 launched on July 26, 1971, and landed on the lunar surface on July 30. During the mission, Scott and lunar module pilot James Irwin collected 170 pounds (~77 kilograms) of lunar material during their more than 18 hours on the Moon's surface.

Image Credit: @nasa

#nasa #space #rover #moon #apollo

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by NASA Artemis on July 27, 2021. May be an image of outdoors and text.

node.text:
This week and next, we are celebrating the 50th anniversary of the Apollo 15 mission — the first mission where astronauts used the Apollo Lunar Surface Drill to gather lunar geological samples.

Now, under #Artemis, the Regolith and Ice Drill for Exploring New Terrain (TRIDENT) will be the key to locating ice and other resources on the Moon. 🔱

Image Credit: Erik van Meijgaarden

#nasa #space #apollo #moon #lunar

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by NASA Artemis on July 21, 2021. May be an image of indoor.

node.text:
Cube + satellite = CubeSat 🧊

On July 14, the Near-Earth Asteroid (NEA) Scout and Lunar IceCube secondary payloads were installed in NASA's Space Launch System rocket’s Orion stage adapter for #Artemis I at @nasakennedy.

Sent to conduct science experiments and technology demonstrations, NEA Scout will be the first CubeSat to travel to an asteroid and Lunar IceCube will search for water ice and other resources from above the surface of the Moon.

First photo: Lunar IceCube
Second photo: NEA Scout packaged sail prior to deployment

Image Credit: @nasa

#nasa #rocket #satellite #asteroid #Moon

On this day in 1969, Apollo 11 carried the first humans to the Moon. 

This #NationalMoonDay, we commemorate the day humans first walked on the lunar surface—and look ahead to our next goal of landing the first woman and first person of color on the Moon with #Artemis.

Image Credits: @nasa

node.text:
A change of scenery 🌳

The Orion spacecraft for the #Artemis I mission recently completed fueling and servicing checks while inside the Multi-Payload Processing Facility at @NASAKennedy in Florida. The capsule has now made it to its next stop on the path to the pad: the spaceport’s Launch Abort System Facility.

Teams with Exploration Ground Systems and @JacobsConnects are now working to add parts of the launch abort system onto the spacecraft. The launch abort system is designed to pull crew away to safety from the SLS rocket in the event of an emergency during launch.

#nasa #SLS #rocket #exploration #Orion

node.text:
#TBT: A dream-like shot from Apollo 16 ✨
 
In this photo from April 23, 1972, the Apollo 16 Command and Service Module (CSM) "Casper" approached the Lunar Module (LM) for their final rendezvous of the mission.
 
@nasaastronauts John W. Young and Charles M. Duke Jr., aboard the LM, were returning to the CSM in lunar orbit after three successful days on the surface of the Moon. Astronaut Thomas K. Mattingly II was in the CSM.
 
Image Credit: @nasa
 
#nasa #Moon #Apollo #exploration

node.text:
Adding to the Artemis I stack 🥞

The #Artemis I mission reached another milestone this week inside the Vehicle Assembly Building (VAB) at @nasakennedy. On July 5, teams with Exploration Ground Systems and contractor @Jacobsconnects stacked the interim cryogenic propulsion stage (ICPS) atop the Space Launch System (SLS) rocket.

The ICPS will fire its RL 10 engine to send the Orion spacecraft toward the Moon. The engine is housed inside the launch vehicle stage adapter, which will protect the engine during launch. The adapter connects the rocket’s core stage with the ICPS.

Before attaching the Orion spacecraft to the rocket, teams will conduct a series of tests to assure all the rocket components are properly communicating with each other, the ground systems equipment, and the Launch Control Center.

Image Credit: NASA/Kim Shiflett

#nasa #SLS #rocket #exploration

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by NASA Artemis on July 04, 2021. May be an image of standing.

node.text:
A view of red, white, and blue 🇺🇸

The American flag was recently repainted on the Vehicle Assembly Building (VAB) at @nasakennedy in Florida. Teams began repainting the meatball and flag on the iconic facility in May 2020 and completed the project in October 2020.

The VAB was last painted in 2007, when repairs where completed after Hurricanes Frances and Jeanne tore 845 panels off the building in 2004.

The flag is 209 feet (~64 meters) long by 110 feet (~34 meters) wide. Each star is more than six feet (~2 meters) in diameter, and each stripe is nine feet (~3 meters) wide. The job took over 500 gallons of paint to repaint the flag and the meatball.

Exploration Ground Systems is overseeing upgrades to the VAB to support the launch of the Space Launch System and Orion for #Artemis missions.

Image Credits: NASA/Ben Smegelsky

#FourthOfJuly #RedWhiteAndBlue #NASA #IndependenceDay #AmericanFlag

node.text:
The worm waiting in High Bay 3 🐛

Pictured here, the @NASA worm logo is emblazoned on the side of the twin Space Launch System boosters in High Bay 3 of the Vehicle Assembly Building at @nasakennedy.

In August 2020, workers with NASA’s Exploration Ground Systems and their contractor Jacobs (@jacobsconnects) started painting the iconic design across two of the booster segments. The team used a laser projector to mask off the logo with tape, then painted the first coat of the logo inside the center’s Rotation, Processing and Surge Facility. The job was completed by adding a second coat of paint, followed by multiple clear coats on the booster.

The worm will be visible while the rocket is on the launch pad and as it soars through Earth’s atmosphere during the launch of Artemis I.

Credit: NASA

#nasa #space #rocket #exploration #SLS

node.text:
Today’s #Artemis progress report: ongoing Space Launch System stacking. 🥪

@NASA’s Exploration Ground Systems and @jacobsconnects teams recently stacked the launch vehicle stage adapter (LVSA) to the rocket’s upper and lower propulsion stages. With the addition of the LVSA, the diameter of the SLS rocket begins to change shape from a wide base to a more narrow point—much like a change in the shape of a pencil from eraser to point.

The 30-foot-tall, cone-shaped piece of hardware connects the SLS rocket’s upper and lower propulsion stages. The adapter also houses the RL10 engine that powers the Interim Cryogenic Propulsion Stage that will send Orion on a precise trajectory to the Moon.

Credit: NASA

#nasa #space #sls #exploration #rocket

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by NASA Artemis on June 28, 2021. May be a black-and-white image of 1 person and indoor.

node.text:
Let’s take a minute to talk about one of our finalists: Arturo Campos!

Campos was born in Laredo, Texas in 1934, hailing from a Mexican-American family. After graduating from the University of Texas with a degree in electrical engineering, Campos worked as a civilian employee supervising aircraft maintenance at Kelly Air Force Base in Texas.

Campos joined NASA in the early 1960s and leveraged his electrical engineering expertise in dozens of projects. He began in research and development of electrical systems for spacecraft, and became one of the go-to figures responsible for the electrical system used in Apollo lunar modules — including the first Moon landing in 1969.

During the Apollo 13 crisis, as the electrical power subsystem manager for the lunar module, Campos worked to reconstruct his plan to provide the command module with enough electrical power to navigate home safely. If it hadn’t been for the procedure Campos and his colleagues put together, it is likely the Apollo 13 mission would not be remembered as the “successful failure” that it is today. Campos and other members of mission control were awarded the Presidential Medal of Freedom by Richard Nixon in 1970.

Check our stories to read more and for the opportunity to vote for Campos!

Credit: @nasa

#nasa #space #Artemis
